{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_3839c615cebc424198fef693","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t=================\n2\trecipe-scrapers\n3\t=================\n4\t\n5\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/github/stars/hhursev/recipe-scrapers?style=social\n6\t    :target: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/\n7\t    :alt: Github\n8\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/recipe-scrapers.svg?\n9\t    :target: https://pypi.org/project/recipe-scrapers/\n10\t    :alt: Version\n11\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/recipe-scrapers\n12\t    :target: https://pypi.org/project/recipe-scrapers/\n13\t    :alt: PyPI - Python Version\n14\t.. image:: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/actions/workflows/unittests.yaml/badge.svg?branch=main\n15\t    :target: unittests\n16\t    :alt: GitHub Actions Unittests\n17\t.. image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/hhursev/recipe-scraper/badge.svg?branch=main&service=github\n18\t    :target: https://coveralls.io/github/hhursev/recipe-scraper?branch=main\n19\t    :alt: Coveralls\n20\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/github/license/hhursev/recipe-scrapers?\n21\t    :target: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/blob/main/LICENSE\n22\t    :alt: License\n23\t\n24\t\n25\tQuick Links\n26\t-----------\n27\t- `Documentation <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com>`_\n28\t- `Supported Sites <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/getting-started/supported-sites/>`_\n29\t- `Contributing Guide <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/contributing/home/>`_\n30\t- `Issue Tracker <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/issues>`_\n31\t- `Share Project Ideas <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/issues/9>`_\n32\t\n33\t\n34\tA Python package for extracting recipe data from cooking websites. Parses recipe information from\n35\teither standard `HTML <https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML>`_ structure,\n36\t`Schema <https://schema.org/>`_ markup (including JSON-LD, Microdata, and RDFa formats) or\n37\t`OpenGraph <https://ogp.me/>`_ metadata.\n38\t\n39\tThe package provides a simple and consistent API for retrieving data such as ingredients, instructions,\n40\tcooking times, and `more <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/contributing/in-depth-guide-scraper-functions/>`_.\n41\t\n42\tCompatible with the Python versions listed above. This package does not circumvent or bypass any\n43\tbot protection measures implemented by websites.\n44\t\n45\t\n46\tInstallation\n47\t------------\n48\t.. code:: shell\n49\t\n50\t    pip install recipe-scrapers\n51\t\n52\t\n53\tBasic Usage\n54\t-----------\n55\t.. code:: python\n56\t\n57\t    from recipe_scrapers import scrape_me\n58\t\n59\t    scraper = scrape_me(\"https://www.allrecipes.com/recipe/158968/spinach-and-feta-turkey-burgers/\")\n60\t    scraper.title()\n61\t    scraper.instructions()\n62\t    scraper.to_json()\n63\t    # for a complete list of methods:\n64\t    # help(scraper)\n65\t\n66\t\n67\tThis package is focused **exclusively on HTML parsing**.\n68\t\n69\tFor advanced implementations, you'll need to implement your own solution for fetching recipe HTMLs\n70\tand managing network requests. The library works best when you provide both the HTML content and\n71\tits source domain.\n72\t\n73\tYou are encouraged to use our *scrape_html* method:\n74\t\n75\t.. code:: python\n76\t\n77\t    from recipe_scrapers import scrape_html\n78\t\n79\tHigher-quality image detection is enabled by default when multiple options are available\n80\ton a page. If you prefer to keep the first image returned by the site, disable the\n81\tbehaviour on a per-call basis or via the global setting:\n82\t\n83\t.. code:: python\n84\t\n85\t    scraper = scrape_html(html, url, best_image=False)\n86\t    image_url = scraper.image()\n87\t\n88\t    from recipe_scrapers.settings import settings\n89\t\n90\t    settings.BEST_IMAGE_SELECTION = False\n91\t\n92\tSupported Sites\n93\t---------------\n94\tWe support a wide range of recipe websites out of the box. Check our\n95\t`supported sites list <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/getting-started/supported-sites/>`_\n96\tfor the full list.\n97\t\n98\tYou can also get the full list programmatically with:\n99\t\n100\t.. code:: python\n101\t\n102\t    from recipe_scrapers import SCRAPERS\n103\t\n104\t    SCRAPERS.keys()\n105\t\n106\t\n107\tContributing\n108\t------------\n109\tWe welcome contributions! Please read our\n110\t`contribution guide <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/contributing/home/>`_ to get started.\n111\t\n112\t\n113\tSpecial Thanks\n114\t--------------\n115\tTo all the `contributors <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/graphs/contributors>`_ who\n116\thelp make this project better!\n117\t\n118\t.. image:: https://contrib.rocks/image?repo=hhursev/recipe-scrapers\n119\t   :target: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/graphs/contributors\n120\t\n121\t\n122\tShare Your Project\n123\t------------------\n124\tHave an idea for using recipe-scrapers? Check out\n125\tour `project ideas wall <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/issues/9>`_ for inspiration\n126\tor to share your own project!\n127\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f465c12b-50e3-4f5d-a2ba-1b51a6f19ce8","uuid":"b4b84078-181c-403c-aeea-0e6cb34083c6","timestamp":"2026-04-09T04:06:51.092Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst","content":"=================\nrecipe-scrapers\n=================\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/github/stars/hhursev/recipe-scrapers?style=social\n    :target: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/\n    :alt: Github\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/recipe-scrapers.svg?\n    :target: https://pypi.org/project/recipe-scrapers/\n    :alt: Version\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/recipe-scrapers\n    :target: https://pypi.org/project/recipe-scrapers/\n    :alt: PyPI - Python Version\n.. image:: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/actions/workflows/unittests.yaml/badge.svg?branch=main\n    :target: unittests\n    :alt: GitHub Actions Unittests\n.. image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/hhursev/recipe-scraper/badge.svg?branch=main&service=github\n    :target: https://coveralls.io/github/hhursev/recipe-scraper?branch=main\n    :alt: Coveralls\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/github/license/hhursev/recipe-scrapers?\n    :target: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/blob/main/LICENSE\n    :alt: License\n\n\nQuick Links\n-----------\n- `Documentation <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com>`_\n- `Supported Sites <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/getting-started/supported-sites/>`_\n- `Contributing Guide <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/contributing/home/>`_\n- `Issue Tracker <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/issues>`_\n- `Share Project Ideas <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/issues/9>`_\n\n\nA Python package for extracting recipe data from cooking websites. Parses recipe information from\neither standard `HTML <https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML>`_ structure,\n`Schema <https://schema.org/>`_ markup (including JSON-LD, Microdata, and RDFa formats) or\n`OpenGraph <https://ogp.me/>`_ metadata.\n\nThe package provides a simple and consistent API for retrieving data such as ingredients, instructions,\ncooking times, and `more <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/contributing/in-depth-guide-scraper-functions/>`_.\n\nCompatible with the Python versions listed above. This package does not circumvent or bypass any\nbot protection measures implemented by websites.\n\n\nInstallation\n------------\n.. code:: shell\n\n    pip install recipe-scrapers\n\n\nBasic Usage\n-----------\n.. code:: python\n\n    from recipe_scrapers import scrape_me\n\n    scraper = scrape_me(\"https://www.allrecipes.com/recipe/158968/spinach-and-feta-turkey-burgers/\")\n    scraper.title()\n    scraper.instructions()\n    scraper.to_json()\n    # for a complete list of methods:\n    # help(scraper)\n\n\nThis package is focused **exclusively on HTML parsing**.\n\nFor advanced implementations, you'll need to implement your own solution for fetching recipe HTMLs\nand managing network requests. The library works best when you provide both the HTML content and\nits source domain.\n\nYou are encouraged to use our *scrape_html* method:\n\n.. code:: python\n\n    from recipe_scrapers import scrape_html\n\nHigher-quality image detection is enabled by default when multiple options are available\non a page. If you prefer to keep the first image returned by the site, disable the\nbehaviour on a per-call basis or via the global setting:\n\n.. code:: python\n\n    scraper = scrape_html(html, url, best_image=False)\n    image_url = scraper.image()\n\n    from recipe_scrapers.settings import settings\n\n    settings.BEST_IMAGE_SELECTION = False\n\nSupported Sites\n---------------\nWe support a wide range of recipe websites out of the box. Check our\n`supported sites list <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/getting-started/supported-sites/>`_\nfor the full list.\n\nYou can also get the full list programmatically with:\n\n.. code:: python\n\n    from recipe_scrapers import SCRAPERS\n\n    SCRAPERS.keys()\n\n\nContributing\n------------\nWe welcome contributions! Please read our\n`contribution guide <https://docs.recipe-scrapers.com/contributing/home/>`_ to get started.\n\n\nSpecial Thanks\n--------------\nTo all the `contributors <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/graphs/contributors>`_ who\nhelp make this project better!\n\n.. image:: https://contrib.rocks/image?repo=hhursev/recipe-scrapers\n   :target: https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/graphs/contributors\n\n\nShare Your Project\n------------------\nHave an idea for using recipe-scrapers? Check out\nour `project ideas wall <https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers/issues/9>`_ for inspiration\nor to share your own project!\n","numLines":127,"startLine":1,"totalLines":127}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_e203a5809ca34a0db958e2e7","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Setup\n2\t\n3\tThank you for your interest in contributing to this project!\n4\t\n5\tFollow these steps to set up your environment for development.\n6\t\n7\t!!! note \"Prerequisites\"\n8\t    This guide assumes you have basic familiarity with Python development, including using `pip`,\n9\t    `virtual environments`, and `git`. These core concepts are beyond the scope of this documentation.\n10\t\n11\t\n12\t!!! warning \"Python Version Requirement\"\n13\t    We strongly recommend using Python 3.11 or above for all development work related to `recipe-scrapers`.\n14\t    This version includes built-in `tomllib` support, which is essential for the project's configuration handling.\n15\t\n16\t\n17\tWe welcome various types of code contributions to `recipe-scrapers`, including:\n18\t\n19\t- Bug fixes\n20\t- New recipe site scrapers\n21\t- Performance improvements\n22\t- Feature enhancements\n23\t- Test coverage improvements\n24\t\n25\t\n26\t## Fork the Repository\n27\t\n28\t1. Navigate to [our repository on GitHub](https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers).\n29\t2. Click the \"Fork\" button in the top right corner to create your own copy of the repository.\n30\t\n31\t\n32\t## Clone Your Fork\n33\t\n34\t```sh\n35\tgit clone https://github.com/<your-username>/recipe-scrapers.git\n36\tcd recipe-scrapers\n37\t```\n38\t\n39\t## Set Upstream Remote\n40\t\n41\t!!! tip \"Upstream Remote\"\n42\t    Setting the upstream remote allows you to sync changes from the original repository to your fork.\n43\t    This is useful to keep your fork up-to-date with the latest changes.\n44\t\n45\t```sh\n46\tgit remote add upstream https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers.git\n47\t```\n48\t\n49\t\n50\t## Create a Virtual Environment\n51\t\n52\tIt's recommended to use a virtual environment to manage dependencies. You can create one using `venv`\n53\t\n54\t```sh\n55\tpython -m venv .venv\n56\tsource .venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: `.venv\\Scripts\\activate`\n57\t```\n58\t\n59\t!!! tip \"Virtual Environment\"\n60\t    Remember to activate your virtual environment each time you work on the project:\n61\t```sh\n62\t    source .venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: .venv\\Scripts\\activate\n63\t```\n64\t\n65\t## Install Dependencies\n66\t\n67\tInstall the required dependencies using `pip`\n68\t\n69\t```sh\n70\tpip install -e \".[all]\"\n71\t```\n72\t\n73\tOur pyproject.toml file lists the installed dependencies and their purposes.\n74\t\n75\t\n76\t## Development Workflow\n77\t\n78\tCreate a new branch for your changes:\n79\t```sh\n80\tgit checkout -b fix/your-fix-name     # for bug fixes\n81\t# or\n82\tgit checkout -b site/website-name     # for new site scrapers\n83\t# or\n84\tgit checkout -b docs/your-addition    # for docs updates\n85\t# or\n86\tgit checkout -b feature/feature-name  # for new features\n87\t```\n88\t\n89\tAfter making your changes, commit them:\n90\t\n91\t```sh\n92\tgit add -p  # Review changes before adding them\n93\tgit commit -m \"meaningful commit message\"\n94\tgit push origin your-branch-name\n95\t```\n96\t\n97\t### Pre-commit Hooks\n98\t\n99\tThe project uses pre-commit hooks to ensure code quality and consistency. These hooks run\n100\tautomatically when you commit changes, handling tasks like:\n101\t\n102\t- Code formatting (black, isort)\n103\t- Linting (flake8)\n104\t- Type checking\n105\t- Other code quality checks\n106\t\n107\t\n108\t## Syncing Your Fork\n109\t\n110\tTo keep your fork up-to-date with the original repository, you can fetch and merge changes from\n111\tthe upstream remote:\n112\t\n113\t```sh\n114\tgit fetch upstream\n115\tgit merge upstream/main\n116\t```\n117\t\n118\tThen create a Pull Request back to the [main repository](https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers)\n119\tfrom your fork.\n120\t\n121\t\n122\tIf you have troubles check out [Submitting A  Pull Request Section](#submitting-a-pull-request).\n123\t\n124\t\n125\t## Submitting a Pull Request\n126\t\n127\t1. Navigate to your fork on GitHub.\n128\t2. Click the \"New pull request\" button.\n129\t3. Ensure the base fork is the original repository and the base branch is `main`.\n130\t4. Fill out the pull request template and submit.\n131\t\n132\t\n133\t## Thank you for contributing!\n134\t\n135\t### What happens after a PR\n136\t\n137\tWhen you submit your PR:\n138\t\n139\t1. Our CI suite will run against your code to ensure everything works as expected. You can run the\n140\t2. tests locally before submitting:\n141\t```sh\n142\tpython -m unittest\n143\t# or\n144\tunittest-parallel --level test\n145\t```\n146\t\n147\t2. Community members and core contributors will review your code. They may:\n148\t    - Request changes or improvements\n149\t    - Suggest alternative approaches\n150\t    - Provide feedback on test coverage\n151\t    - Ask for documentation updates\n152\t\n153\t3. Once approved, a core contributor will merge your PR\n154\t    - Your contribution will be included in the next release\n155\t    - Tackle any follow-up improvements in subsequent PRs\n156\t\n157\tDon't worry if your first PR needs some adjustments - this is normal and part of the collaborative\n158\tdevelopment process!\n159\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f465c12b-50e3-4f5d-a2ba-1b51a6f19ce8","uuid":"3759acc1-a66a-4eb6-87d4-bfb0f6fac575","timestamp":"2026-04-09T04:06:51.094Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/contributing/setup.md","content":"# Setup\n\nThank you for your interest in contributing to this project!\n\nFollow these steps to set up your environment for development.\n\n!!! note \"Prerequisites\"\n    This guide assumes you have basic familiarity with Python development, including using `pip`,\n    `virtual environments`, and `git`. These core concepts are beyond the scope of this documentation.\n\n\n!!! warning \"Python Version Requirement\"\n    We strongly recommend using Python 3.11 or above for all development work related to `recipe-scrapers`.\n    This version includes built-in `tomllib` support, which is essential for the project's configuration handling.\n\n\nWe welcome various types of code contributions to `recipe-scrapers`, including:\n\n- Bug fixes\n- New recipe site scrapers\n- Performance improvements\n- Feature enhancements\n- Test coverage improvements\n\n\n## Fork the Repository\n\n1. Navigate to [our repository on GitHub](https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers).\n2. Click the \"Fork\" button in the top right corner to create your own copy of the repository.\n\n\n## Clone Your Fork\n\n```sh\ngit clone https://github.com/<your-username>/recipe-scrapers.git\ncd recipe-scrapers\n```\n\n## Set Upstream Remote\n\n!!! tip \"Upstream Remote\"\n    Setting the upstream remote allows you to sync changes from the original repository to your fork.\n    This is useful to keep your fork up-to-date with the latest changes.\n\n```sh\ngit remote add upstream https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers.git\n```\n\n\n## Create a Virtual Environment\n\nIt's recommended to use a virtual environment to manage dependencies. You can create one using `venv`\n\n```sh\npython -m venv .venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: `.venv\\Scripts\\activate`\n```\n\n!!! tip \"Virtual Environment\"\n    Remember to activate your virtual environment each time you work on the project:\n```sh\n    source .venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: .venv\\Scripts\\activate\n```\n\n## Install Dependencies\n\nInstall the required dependencies using `pip`\n\n```sh\npip install -e \".[all]\"\n```\n\nOur pyproject.toml file lists the installed dependencies and their purposes.\n\n\n## Development Workflow\n\nCreate a new branch for your changes:\n```sh\ngit checkout -b fix/your-fix-name     # for bug fixes\n# or\ngit checkout -b site/website-name     # for new site scrapers\n# or\ngit checkout -b docs/your-addition    # for docs updates\n# or\ngit checkout -b feature/feature-name  # for new features\n```\n\nAfter making your changes, commit them:\n\n```sh\ngit add -p  # Review changes before adding them\ngit commit -m \"meaningful commit message\"\ngit push origin your-branch-name\n```\n\n### Pre-commit Hooks\n\nThe project uses pre-commit hooks to ensure code quality and consistency. These hooks run\nautomatically when you commit changes, handling tasks like:\n\n- Code formatting (black, isort)\n- Linting (flake8)\n- Type checking\n- Other code quality checks\n\n\n## Syncing Your Fork\n\nTo keep your fork up-to-date with the original repository, you can fetch and merge changes from\nthe upstream remote:\n\n```sh\ngit fetch upstream\ngit merge upstream/main\n```\n\nThen create a Pull Request back to the [main repository](https://github.com/hhursev/recipe-scrapers)\nfrom your fork.\n\n\nIf you have troubles check out [Submitting A  Pull Request Section](#submitting-a-pull-request).\n\n\n## Submitting a Pull Request\n\n1. Navigate to your fork on GitHub.\n2. Click the \"New pull request\" button.\n3. Ensure the base fork is the original repository and the base branch is `main`.\n4. Fill out the pull request template and submit.\n\n\n## Thank you for contributing!\n\n### What happens after a PR\n\nWhen you submit your PR:\n\n1. Our CI suite will run against your code to ensure everything works as expected. You can run the\n2. tests locally before submitting:\n```sh\npython -m unittest\n# or\nunittest-parallel --level test\n```\n\n2. Community members and core contributors will review your code. They may:\n    - Request changes or improvements\n    - Suggest alternative approaches\n    - Provide feedback on test coverage\n    - Ask for documentation updates\n\n3. Once approved, a core contributor will merge your PR\n    - Your contribution will be included in the next release\n    - Tackle any follow-up improvements in subsequent PRs\n\nDon't worry if your first PR needs some adjustments - this is normal and part of the collaborative\ndevelopment process!\n","numLines":159,"startLine":1,"totalLines":159}}}
